          Additional informationPublisher’s note Springer Nature remains neutral with regard to jurisdictional claims in published maps and institutional affiliations.Extended dataExtended Data Fig. 1 Temporal evolution in thermal damping and contribution of zonal wind variability and thermocline feedback to changes in ENSO amplitude.a, Time evolution of surface air–sea heat flux anomalies response to Niño3.4 SST index (W m−2 per °C; positive downward) under the historical and SSP5-8.5 emission scenarios using a 31-year running window. The shading shows the range of one s.d. of the multi-model ensemble mean in each year based on a bootstrap test (see Methods). The time axis represents the middle year of each time window. b, Histogram of 10,000 realizations from a bootstrap method for the inter-model correlation coefficient between projected change in zonal wind stress (tauu) variability trend and projected change in Niño3.4 SST variability trend. The projected change is calculated as the difference between 2015-2050 and 2050-2085. To assess the statistical significance of the inter-model correlation coefficient, we constructed 10,000 realizations of the inter-model correlation. In each realization, models are resampled randomly with a model allowed to be selected again during the random resampling process, such that we can calculate the correlation coefficient between zonal wind variability and ENSO SST variability across the resampled models. The distribution of the 10,000 correlation coefficients is shown along the x-axis, with percentages on the y-axis representing the fraction of realizations falling within each bin. The multi-realization mean correlation coefficient as indicated by the red line, and its one standard deviation range of the multi-realization, are shown in the upper left of the panel. c, The same as b, but for the statistics of the inter-model correlation between projected change in thermocline feedback trend and projected change in ENSO SST variability trend.Extended Data Fig. 2 Influence of model biases on the time evolution of tropical SST variability.a, Time evolution in Niño3.4 SST variability based on selected models (Supplementary Table 1) that can simulate realistic ENSO nonlinearity5. b, As in a, but for non-selected models. c and d, The same as a and b, but for IOD based on IOD nonlinearity as model selection criteria6. e and f, The same as a and b, but for Atlantic Niño/Niña based on mean state simulation as model selection criteria4. Note that the non-selected models may include models that are not assessed by the past studies.Extended Data Fig. 3 Projected changes in tropical SST variability under historical and SSP1-2.6 emission scenarios.a, Time evolution of DJF ENSO (Niño3.4; 170°W-120°W, 5°S-5°N) interannual variability (°C) (solid line with shading) based on all available CMIP6 models under the historical and SSP1-2.6 emission scenarios (see Supplementary Table 1) using a 31-year running window. The shading shows the range of one s.d. of the multi-model ensemble mean in each year based on a bootstrap test. The multi-colored curve corresponding to the right Y axis represents the evolution of the 31-years trend of ENSO variability (°C per 100 years), with colors representing percentage of models agreeing on the sign of the multi-model ensemble mean of the trend. b, and c, As in a, but for SON DMI index (50°E-70°E, 10°S-10°N minus 90°E-110°E, 10°S-0°N) and JJA ATL3 index (3°S-3°N, 20°W-0°), respectively.Supplementary informationSupplementary Information (download PDF )Supplementary Table 1.Peer Review File (download PDF )Rights and permissionsSpringer Nature or its licensor (e.g. a society or other partner) holds exclusive rights to this article under a publishing agreement with the author(s) or other rightsholder(s); author self-archiving of the accepted manuscript version of this article is solely governed by the terms of such publishing agreement and applicable law.Reprints and permissionsA